[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Lewis is a pleasant 57-year-old gentleman from Newport News California.  His oncologic history is as follows.
1.  December 29, 2009:  He presented with a two- to three-month history of low abdominal pain.  Chills and a 30-pound weight-loss over two years.  A CT-scan was obtained which revealed a 5.2-cm cystic growth in the subcapsular area near the right lobe of the liver.  Also noted was an abnormal soft-tissue density causing a mass effect off the cecum.
2.  January 19, 2010:  He underwent a colonoscopy which documented two lesions.  One was a-1.1-cm growth in the rectum.  Pathology was positive for tubulovillous adenocarcinoma with low-grade dysplasia and a focus of high-grade dysplasia.  The second nodule was in the cecum and was biopsied positive for invasive adenocarcinoma.  Additional testing was negative for Lynch syndrome.
3.  February 2, 2010:  He was taken to surgery by Dr. Reed from Colorectal Surgery and Dr. Anderson, and he underwent a right hemicolectomy and excision of a perihepatic adhesion.  Surgical pathology revealed that the tissue from the perihepatic adhesion was positive for metastatic grade 2 (4) adenocarcinoma consistent with colon primary.  It was a cystic mass almost entirely filled with mucin and surrounded by a fibrous wall.  Right hemicolectomy revealed an invasive grade 2 (4) adenocarcinoma located at the ileocecal valve.  All surgical resected margins were negative.   Also 2 (11) regional lymph nodes were positive and showed extranodal extension.  Hence, it was staged as T3, NIB, MI.
Mr. Lewis returns for discussion of adjuvant therapy.  He has recovered completely from the surgical procedure.  His appetite is good.  His weight has remained stable.  He has good energy levels and has an ECOG performance score of 1.

